sysdep-2-3            Xerox Quintus Prolog System-Dependent Features Manual           Section 2-3: Executing Lisp Functions from Within PrologThe built-in predicates lisp_apply/3 and lisp_apply/3 enable you to executeLisp functions from within Prolog.  The format of these predicates islisp_apply(FunctionName, [ListOfArguments], ReturnValue)lisp_apply(FunctionName, [ListOfArguments])This predicate applies the specified Lisp function to the list of argumentsgiven and, in the case of lisp_apply/3, produces a value that is unified withReturnValue.  Of course, lisp_apply/2 is useful only to produce side-effects.For example,            | ?- lisp_apply('CONS', [1,2], X).            X=[1|2]            | ?- lisp_apply('SETQ', ['FOO','T']).            yesNOTE:  lisp_apply/2 and lisp_apply/3 are generally less efficient than the Lispinterface (described below).  For this reason it should not be used to callLisp code in tight loops.